Based on the summary of the data, three explanatory variables attitude, surf and stra are picked to fit a regression model against exam points as they have the highest absolute correlation value.

The new linear fit summary shows that the P value has improved by a factor of 10. the there is a positive relationship between attitude and points where every 1 unit increase in attitude results in a 3.5255 unit increase in exam points. However, the linear fit has a low multiple R-squared value of 0.1906, which indicates that only some of the variability of the data is around its mean.

Model validation

The linear regression model assumes that: - The data follows a linear relationship - The errors are normally distributed - The errors are not correlated - The errors have constant variance

The normal QQ plot confirms that the data between attitude and exam points are normally distributed since the most of the data fits in on the normal line. The residual vs fitted plot shows that the data plots are similarly spread as fitted values increases, implying that the errors have constant variance.

The data represents students achievement in secondary education of two Portuguese schools. The data attributes students grades, demographic, social and school related feastures, and are collected using school reports and questionnaires. Average of two grades, Portuguese and Mathematics, are obtained from their 1st, 2nd and 3rd period (G1, G2 and G3 respectively). Since G3 has strong has a strong correlation with G1 and G2, only G3 is used for analysis. alc_use represents the average alcohol consumption per week while we assumed that high useage of alcohol (high_use) is more than 2. More deatils can be found in https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance.

Exploring 4 variables with possible relationship with alcohol consumption

To study the effect of alcohol usage, four variables are choosen. They are: health, grades, quality of family relationship and frequency of going out. The hypothesis are as follows:

  • H1 = High usage of alcohol may deteroriate health status
  • H2 = High usage of alcohol may affect grades badly
  • H3 = High usage of alcohol may dampen the relationship with family due to possible alcoholism leading to disputes and violence. Conversely, a poor relationship with family may lead to higher alcohol consumption.
  • H4 = High usage of alcohol may be due to the occurence of going out a lot to drink with friends

The table shows the average grades and scores for health, grade and family relationship. They are splited into four categories depending on geneder and whether there is high usage of alcohol. The box plot shows the spread of the 4 variables compared to alcohol consumption.

It seems that for H1, the usage of alcohol does not really affect the quality of life. They share similar mean score and most of them have median at 4. It seems that females not having high usage of alcohol may have poorer health due to lower median, but a majority of them stays in the higher score region. Therefore, H1 is unlikely to happen.

For H2, both females have very similar mean grades, while males who do not drink as much have higher mean grades than their counterpart. This observation is also evident from the box plot, but requires more in-depth analysis to prove this hypothesi since the females are not affected.

Regardless of gender, H3 may be likely as the mean scores of family relationship for high consumption of alcohol are lower. While they all share very similar median, The box plot also shows that a majority of high usage drinkers are below the median, while for low usage drinkers the scores are above the median.

Lastly, high usage drinkers are more likely to go out than low usage for both genders. THis observation is more prominent for males.

Since only famrel and goout are significant, we will only be looking at these two variables. To obtain the true coefficient, we have to get the difference the intercept and variable. Hence, the true coeff for famrel is 0.58287 and go out is 1.9378 .The odds ratio for goout is >1, which suggests that the more you go out, the more likely you are to have high alcohol consumption. This supports H4. For famrel, since it is below 1, the better family relationship you have, the less likely you are to have high alcohol usage. THis supporst the 2nd part of H3.

The plot describes the PC components when the data is reduced using the PCA method.PCA essentially transforms the dataset by projecting them onto a set of orthogonal axes. It finds the best linear combination of the original variables so that the variance or spread along the new variable is maximum. The standard deviation of Principal components represent the eigenvalues. For the sake of learning, we will only be looking at PC1 and PC2 since they hold the highest percentage.

The variables are as follows: - Expected.Edu is the espected education in years - GNI refers to Gross National Income per capita - GNI.HDI.RANK refers to the substraction of HDI rank from GNI rank (i.e GNI minus HDI) - Mat.Mor Ratio refers to the number of deaths per 100 000 live births. - Birth.Rate refers to the adolescent births per 1000 women ages 15 - 19. - Parliment percentage refers to the percentage of parliment seats taken up by females - F2Edu & M2Edu refers to secondardy education of both female and male respectively. - FLab & MLab refers the labour force of both female and male respectively. - EduRatio and LabRatio refers to the ratio of female over male for both education and labour respectively.

In the non standardised biplot, the standard dev of PC1 is way higher as compared to the other components.As such, the percentage attributed to PC1 is way higher than the rest. This means that only the first maximum amount of variance if captured but any subsequent is not. This would misrepresent the data, as the angles between each variance arrows and the angle between variable and the axis are important in determining their correlation. As such, standardisation helps to scale each components such that they are independent of each others magnitude.

From the standardised biplot, we can now see that the std dev is much closer to each other. As such, we are able to see that the proportion of each PC is more significant than before. From the biplot, we can observe the correlation between each variable (arrow) and against the axis.A few observations can be made: 1)Mat Mor Rat and Birth Rate have very high correlation, which is obvious since the numberr of deaths is based on 100 000birth, which is affected by the birth rate 2) Expected education, GNI, Life expectancy and edu ratio are highly correlated. This is also obvious because gross national income do affect the quality of life and affordable education. 3) Lab ratio and parilment percentage are correlated but not as high as the above 2 points. Since parliment is also a form of labour/job, then the ratio can be expected to be similar. 4) Other than lab ratio and parliment percentage, the 6 other variables are highly correlated to PC1. This means that these few variables are accounted for the maximum spread of the data i.e.mat.mor.ratio and birth rate in a positive manner, the other 4 in a negative manner. 5) The last two variable contributes positively to PC2.

Note: I read up on PCA and found that often, screen plot is done to choose the important PC components. When the sum of PC percentage exceeds 95%, the remaninding PC values can be ignored.

The mca shows the variance of each dimension. The highest % is only 15% which suggest that it will only explain 15% of the variance. Multiple dimensions would be needed to tell us the full story. Looking at the categorical variables, under dim 1, both how and where have the largest value, which suggest that they are highly correlated. For Dim 2, we have how and where.

From the biplot, we can obtain both the correlation between each individual cataegory from their angles between each other, as well as the association via the distance from the origin. Based on the MCA factor map, it seems that most earl grey drinkers prefer to have milk (since their angle is very small). There is slight preference for earl grey drinks to have sugar in it. Black tea and green tea drinkers seems to like to have their tea without sugar. Those who bought their tea from the tea shop often have unpackaged tea, which makes sense since shops normally sells unpackaged ones. As for chain store, they usually sell tea bags that can be readily prepared for convenience. However, all these insights should be taken with a pinch of salt, since both Dim 1 and Dim 2 add up to about 30% only, which suggest that 70% of the variance is not represented in this plot.

This dataset describes an in vivo test of 16 rats from 3 different diet groups. Their weight were measured a few times with intervals at day 1, 8, 15 22, 29, 36, 43, 44, 50, 57 and 64.

Drawing the plot

ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = Time, y = Weight, linetype = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(RATSL$Weight), max(RATSL$Weight)))

Each line represents the weight of one mouse throughout the 69 days of duration. We can observe that the weight of all groups increases over time. Group 1 diet have the lowest through the whole period of time, while both group 2 and group 3 have very similar weight. (except for the higest weight in group 2). However, since the mice have very different weights, we would standardise them to get a better comparison.

Golden standardisation and tracking phenomenon

RATSS <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Group,ID) %>%
  mutate(stdweight = ((Weight-mean(Weight))/sd(Weight))) %>%
  ungroup()

From the results of ANOVA, we can see that the baseline (in this case weight on day 1) is strongly related to the weight taken after day 1 since the P value is highly singinicant (Very small). However, there is no evidence of diet difference even after conditioning to day 1 as the P value is above 0.05 (Assuming we set at P<0.05.

This dataset describes a clinical trial of 40 men randonmly assigned to two treatments, as well as the brief psychiatric rating scale (BRPS) measured before treatment and at a weekly intervals for a total of 8 weeks.18 levels of symptoms are measured such as hostility, suspiciousness, hallucinations and grandiosity - each are rated against a scale from 1 (not present) to 7 (extremely severe). The sum of scale (I presumed) is then used to evaluate patients suspected of having schizophrenia

Plotting data

ggplot(BPRSL, aes(x = week, y = bprs, linetype = subject)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ treatment, labeller = label_both) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(BPRSL$bprs), max(BPRSL$bprs)))

BPRS for both groups decreases as the week goes by. Interestingly, the bprs for treatment 2 is generally higher than treatment 1. This could be due to the higher starting value of brps of treatment 2 as compared to treatment 1.
